profile_positions.description:
We produced and presented a synthesis about series of Intergovernmental Conferences (IGCs) has been organised by the UN General Assembly to develop a binding legal instrument for the sustainable use and management of biodiversity in national jurisdictions. Three sessions have been completed so far between 2018 and 2019; the pandemic of (COVID-19) has prevented the fourth session scheduled for 2020. The sessions were chaired by Ms Rena Lee of Singapore in New York (USA), who proposed an organisation of work into informal groups, which were discussed under four main themes.
- Marine genetic resources (MGR), benefit sharing issues 
- Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA);
- Area-based management tools (ABMT), including marine protected areas;
- Capacity building and transfer of marine technologies (CB & TT).
In this research, we first explain the origin of these debates between the different parliaments. We looked at marine genetic resources and benefit sharing. We also explored the management tools and capacity building for the exploitation of marine genetic resources. At the end, we discussed some perspectives for the fourth session 2022, issues under negotiation for the finalisation of the treaty.
